---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

// Toggle this to true after Margaret's review and approval call.
const margaretApproved = false;
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="About · America's School Trust Library"
      description="A joint project of Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL) and Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL)."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-archive-paper text-ink" data-source-id="about-page">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-prose p-4 sm:p-8">
      <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
        <h1>About America's School Trust Library</h1>

        <h2>Mission</h2>
        <p>
          America's School Trust Library is the evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds. It exists to make the legal architecture, financial scale, and political accountability of these trusts visible — to journalists, lawyers, legislators, trustees, and citizens.
        </p>

        <h2>A joint project</h2>
        <p>The Library is a joint project of two affiliated 501(c)(3) nonprofits:</p>
        <p>
          <strong>Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL)</strong> is the national organization, founded to advance fiduciary integrity in America's school trust lands and funds across all twenty land-grant states. ASTL's organizational page lives at <a href="https://schooltrustlands.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">schooltrustlands.org</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL)</strong> is ASTL's Oregon affiliate and the active plaintiff in Oregon's current trust-breach litigation, including the January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory in <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>. OASTL's organizational page lives at <a href="https://oastl.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">oastl.org</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Library is the public-facing evidentiary archive both organizations rely on. ASTL contributes the national scope and per-state field reporting; OASTL contributes the Oregon case docket, primary sources, and the working-test-case analysis that makes the architecture concrete. The two voices stay audible in the Reading Room — encyclopedia entries are the long, footnoted history; ASTL's per-state notes appear as the field annotation; OASTL substrate appears at <a href="/court/oregon-current-case/">/court/oregon-current-case/</a>, <a href="/reading/us-or/history/">/reading/us-or/history/</a>, and <a href="/reading/us-or/research/">/reading/us-or/research/</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>Substrate and method</h2>
        <p>
          The library is built on a five-layer Knowledge Stack: primary sources (statutes, court opinions, treaties, historical maps, expert declarations); canonical claims (atomized facts and arguments, every one cited to source); audience models (different readers need different pieces); a toolchain of human and AI editors; and the deliverables you see on these pages. The substrate is documented and version-controlled; the build pipeline is reproducible.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every figure on this site carries a confidence badge. Every blank cell is a signal — most often that a state has not disclosed the underlying data. Visible incompleteness is the path to credibility for a public ledger of public trusts.
        </p>

        <h2>Team</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dave Sullivan</strong> — President, Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands; retired professor; lead OASTL plaintiff in Oregon's trust-breach litigation.</li>
          <li><strong>Margaret Bird</strong> — President, Advocates for School Trust Lands; national domain authority on school trust lands; co-author of the encyclopedia.</li>
          <li><strong>Daniel Zene Crowe</strong> — OASTL General Counsel; lead on the 2024 Oregon case (Coos County 24CV38372).</li>
          <li><strong>Natalie Scott</strong> — Lead on the 2023 Oregon case; argued the January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory.</li>
          <li><strong>Laura</strong> — Legal research bridge across both cases.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Contact and corrections</h2>
        <p>
          For corrections, source additions, or story tips: <a href="https://github.com/dave-schooltrustlands/schooltrustlands-encyclopedia/issues">GitHub issues</a>. For organizational contact, see <a href="https://schooltrustlands.org">schooltrustlands.org</a> (ASTL) or <a href="https://oastl.org">oastl.org</a> (OASTL). Citation guidance: <a href="/about/cite/">/about/cite/</a>.
        </p>

        <hr class="archival-divider">

        <section class={`signature-block ${margaretApproved ? 'approved' : 'pending'}`}>
          <p class="signature-margaret">
            <span class="name">Margaret Bird</span><br>
            <span class="role">President, Advocates for School Trust Lands</span>
            {!margaretApproved && <span class="pending-note"><em>Pending review and sign-off.</em></span>}
          </p>
          <p class="signature-dave">
            <span class="name">Dave Sullivan</span><br>
            <span class="role">President, Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands</span>
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
